\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smallholder farmers in low- and middle-income countries adopt modern agricultural inputs and technologies – such as improved seed varieties and inorganic fertilizers – at rates below what their potential returns justify 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doi:10.1126/science.1151062,doi:10.1086/714444,10.1257/jep.36.1.33"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A large literature examines why adoption of these innovations remains limited despite their promise to increase agricultural productivity.
 As reviewed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/jep.36.1.33"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 proposed explanations include credit,
 liquidity,
 and savings constraints;
 limited access to insurance;
 information frictions;
 high transaction costs and poor infrastructure;
 and imperfections in labor and land markets.
 An important additional explanation for the limited adoption of these innovations is farmers’ beliefs about the performance of agricultural inputs sold in local markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Agricultural input markets are often characterized by substantial uncertainty about input performance.
 In the market for high-yielding maize seed
