\end_inset

high-yielding maize varieties
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to both open-pollinated varieties (OPVs) and hybrids that have been genetically improved through breeding programs.
 We explain the terminology and our rationale for using this terminology in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.1 Context on seeds and their quality"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 in Uganda,
 several studies document quality concerns along the supply chain.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bold2017lemon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that locally sold hybrid seed contains less than 50% authentic seed.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 document improper handling and storage of maize seed purchased from retailers,
 while 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Ilukor2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show using DNA fingerprinting that seed quality declines along the supply chain relative to samples from seed companies.
 Recent evidence further suggests that the formal seed certification system fails to provide farmers with a reliable signal of seed quality 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/1477-9552.70002"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Such quality concerns increase farmers’ uncertainty about the performance of seed purchased from agro-dealers,
 a critical distribution channel for agricultural technologies.
 Agro-dealers are highly local,
 small-scale businesses that sell seeds and other inputs such as agrochemicals and serve as an important interface between seed suppliers and farmers.
 The crucial role of Agro-dealers has been highlighted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dar2020private"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Beyond this direct effect,
 quality uncertainty distorts farmers’ complementary input decisions.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Bulte2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that when farmers are uncertain about seed quality,
 they allocate less labor,
 reducing the gains from improved varieties.
 Lower yields,
 in turn,
 make it harder for farmers to learn about the profitability of improved seed varieties,
 slowing adoption over time.
 This illustrates a broader challenge:
 learning about input performance from own experience is difficult in agricultural production,
 where outcomes depend on complex interactions among inputs,
 weather,
 soil conditions,
 pests,
 and management practices.
 As a result,
 individual farmers may find it difficult to infer whether observed yields reflect seed performance or other production factors,
 slowing their learning about the profitability of improved seed and discouraging engagement with agro-dealers in favor of available alternatives such as farmer-saved seed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the same time,
 information about seed performance is dispersed across many farmers who each observe only their own outcomes.
 While farmers may exchange experiences within their social networks,
 these conversations typically involve small numbers of peers and may not capture the broader distribution of experiences with seed sold by agro-dealers.
 As a result,
 farmers rarely observe enough independent experiences to form reliable expectations about seed performance.
 This fragmentation of information limits the extent to which farmers can learn collectively about seed performance in local markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper studies whether aggregating information about other farmers’ experiences can help resolve uncertainty about seed performance and influence adoption decisions.
 We introduce a system that collects farmers’ evaluations of maize seed purchased from agro-dealers and aggregates them into ratings summarizing the experiences of multiple farmers.
 These ratings are disseminated to both farmers and agro-dealers before the following planting season.
 By aggregating experiences across many farmers operating under similar conditions,
 the system provides a signal about seed performance that individual farmers may find difficult to obtain through their own experimentation.
 Unlike marketing claims,
 certification,
 or regulatory quality assurance systems,
 the ratings are based on farmers’ realized production outcomes and therefore reflect actual seed performance in local farming conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We test this approach in a randomized controlled trial (RCT) involving approximately 3,500 smallholder farmers and associated 350 agro-dealers in the market for high-yielding maize varieties in eastern Uganda over two agricultural seasons.
 Exposure to aggregated peer ratings increases farmers’ perceptions of the performance of seed sold by agro-dealers and leads to higher adoption of high-yielding maize seed purchased from these sellers.
 Treated farmers also achieve higher productivity and improved harvest outcomes.
 At the same time,
 we find no evidence that the intervention improves the underlying performance of seed sold by agro-dealers or induces farmers to switch between agro-dealers.
 These findings are consistent with the intervention affecting farmers’ beliefs about seed performance rather than changes in seed performance or seller selection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By providing evidence on how aggregating peer information about seed performance can effectively influence farmers’ beliefs and adoption decisions,
 our study contributes to the literature on agricultural technology adoption.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/jep.36.1.33"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 review key barriers to adoption,
 while 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MICHELSON2023102424"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 highlight the role of input quality uncertainty.
 Our paper advances this literature in three ways.
 First,
 most studies focus on regulatory seed quality assurance systems such as certification.
 We test an innovative intervention with several advantages relative to other sources of information about seed performance:
 it captures multiple dimensions of seed quality that matter to farmers,
 reaches farmers who do not typically purchase from agro-dealers,
 is decentralized and does not rely on institutional capacity or government trust,
 and is agnostic with respect to seed performance,
 yielding insights for both public policy and the private sector.
 Second,
 together with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dar2020private"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 our study is among the few that connect the farmer perspective with the agro-dealer perspective,
 providing a fuller picture than studies focusing on buyers or sellers alone.
 Third,
 the combination of positive treatment effects on perceptions,
 adoption,
 and productivity suggests that farmers’ prior beliefs about seed performance were overly pessimistic.
 These pessimistic beliefs help explain why adoption of agro-dealer seed remains below welfare-optimal levels.
 While overly pessimistic beliefs have been documented in fertilizer markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 we provide the first evidence of this mechanism in seed markets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More broadly,
 our paper relates to a literature on the impact of crowd-sourced quality information on market outcomes.
 The rise of digital platforms and e-commerce has enabled consumers to share feedback widely,
 and a growing body of research examines the effects of such reviews 
