\begin_layout Section
Conceptual framework
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Beliefs and seed purchasing decisions under performance uncertainty
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section develops a conceptual framework for farmers’ decisions to purchase seed from agro-dealers in settings characterized by seed performance uncertainty and constrained learning from own experience.
 In such settings,
 beliefs about seed performance are central to purchase decisions,
 and aggregated peer information can influence behavior by shaping perceived performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Purchasing seed from agro-dealers with outside options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Smallholder farmers typically have access to agro-dealers while also facing multiple alternative channels for sourcing seed,
 including farmer-saved seed,
 informal exchanges,
 and seed distributed through public or non-governmental programs.
 The presence of these outside options implies that purchasing seed from an agro-dealer is a choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Learning from own experience
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Learning about seed performance from own experience is noisy,
 slow,
 and costly.
 Agricultural outcomes depend on many factors – such as rainfall,
 soil conditions,
 pest pressure,
 complementary inputs,
 and management practices – some of which are stochastic and others of which interact.
 After a single season,
 farmers therefore cannot determine whether the yield they observe reflects seed performance or the realization of other production conditions,
 making individual learning noisy.
 Because performance signals arrive only once per agricultural season,
 learning from own experience is slow.
 Moreover,
 seed choice typically requires committing land and labor for an entire season,
 making experimentation costly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Beliefs about agro-dealer seed performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The decision to purchase seed from an agro-dealer depends on farmers’ beliefs about the expected performance of such seed relative to available alternatives,
 taking into account the resources required for purchase.
 When expected performance is perceived to be uncertain or low,
 farmers may avoid engaging with agro-dealers and instead rely on outside options,
 such as farmer-saved seed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Farmers’ prior beliefs about the expected performance of seed from agro-dealers are shaped by their own past experiences as well as by locally shared information.
 Such locally shared information typically reflects a small number of neighbors or acquaintances and may be incomplete,
 selectively transmitted,
 or idiosyncratic.
 As a result,
 it may not reflect average seed performance.
 Given the learning constraints described above,
 such beliefs are difficult to correct:
 after a single season,
 farmers often cannot determine whether an observed outcome reflects seed performance or other production conditions.
 As a result,
 imprecise or biased beliefs about seed performance can persist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While the framework remains agnostic about the direction of belief bias,
 several strands of evidence suggest that farmers’ beliefs may be overly pessimistic relative to true seed performance.
 Evidence from fertilizer markets shows that farmers often underestimate input quality relative to objective measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "MICHELSON2021102579,https://doi.org/10.1111/ajae.12466"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and recent work on maize seed in Uganda suggests that farmers’ perceptions may be more pessimistic than warranted by measured performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Insights from psychology and economics further point in this direction:
 negative information is more salient,
 spreads faster,
 and receives disproportionate weight in social learning under noisy production conditions,
 which can skew belief formation toward pessimism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "neg_bias,vaish2008not,10.1257/aer.100.1.35,hornik2015information"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "wossen2022misperceiving"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 does not provide evidence of negative bias in farmers’ beliefs.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Belief updating through aggregated peer information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When farmers’ beliefs about seed performance are imprecise or biased,
 information interventions can shape belief formation.
 In particular,
 information that aggregates the experiences of farmers who have purchased seed from agro-dealers provides a summary signal of that performance and may complement or substitute for individual learning.
 The way such information affects beliefs depends on farmers’ prior purchasing experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Farmers with prior purchasing experience:

\series default
 For farmers who have previously purchased seed from agro-dealers,
 aggregated peer information complements own learning by pooling outcomes across many purchasers operating under similar conditions.
 From a Bayesian perspective,
 this increases the effective sample size underlying belief formation and mitigates the learning constraints described above.
 As a result,
 such information primarily affects the precision of beliefs rather than their level.
 The aggregate signal these farmers receive is,
 by construction,
 a structured summary of the experiences of farmers who have purchased seed from agro-dealers,
 thereby reducing the influence of any single realization and drawing individual beliefs closer to the cross-farmer average.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Farmers without prior purchasing experience:

\series default
 For farmers who have not previously purchased seed from agro-dealers,
 beliefs about seed performance are formed largely in the absence of own learning and may instead reflect locally shared narratives.
 For these farmers,
 aggregated peer information does more than reduce noise:
 when it differs from prior beliefs,
 it can shift expectations about seed performance and thereby affect the threshold for initial engagement with agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adoption decisions under belief uncertainty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adoption decisions reflect how farmers translate beliefs about seed performance into purchasing behavior,
 taking into account both the level of perceived performance and the uncertainty surrounding it.
 As in the previous subsection,
 the adoption response differs by farmers’ prior experience purchasing seed from agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Farmers with prior purchasing experience:

\series default
 For farmers who have previously purchased seed from agro-dealers,
 aggregated peer information mainly affects the precision of beliefs.
 By reducing uncertainty around seed performance,
 information can increase confidence.
 While this does not change average beliefs,
 greater precision can increase adoption by reducing hesitation or perceived ambiguity around seed purchase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Farmers without prior purchasing experience:

\series default
 For farmers who have not previously purchased seed from agro-dealers,
 aggregated peer information can affect adoption by shifting beliefs about seed performance.
 When the aggregated signal is more favorable than prior beliefs,
 it increases the likelihood of adoption;
 when it is less favorable,
 it decreases adoption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conceptual framework rests on a set of assumptions that define the conditions under which aggregated peer information can update farmers’ beliefs about agro-dealer seed performance and,
 in turn,
 influence adoption decisions under performance uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Farmers have meaningful outside options to purchasing seed from agro-dealers.
 OK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Baseline market institutions do not provide strong or universally trusted performance guarantees for seed sold through agro-dealers.
 OK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Farmers hold prior beliefs about seed performance at agro-dealers that are sufficiently imprecise and/or biased for belief updating to affect adoption decisions.
 OK
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Individual learning about seed performance through own experience is sufficiently noisy,
 slow,
 and costly that beliefs do not rapidly self-correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Individual experiences provide noisy but approximately unbiased signals around the true mean,
 so that aggregating experiences across many farmers produces an informative signal about seed performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Aggregated peer ratings are perceived as sufficiently relevant and credible for farmers to update beliefs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Conditional welfare assumption:
 On average,
 aggregated peer ratings move the beliefs of farmers who rely on them closer to the true performance of seed sold through agro-dealers relative to outside options,
 so that adoption decisions move toward the welfare-optimal level rather than away from it.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The welfare consequences depend on how the information conveyed by experienced farmers compares both to true relative seed performance and to the prior beliefs of farmers who rely on the signal.
 Ratings need not be perfectly accurate to be welfare-improving.
 When the rating signal moves inexperienced farmers’ beliefs closer to true relative performance - by correcting either overly pessimistic or overly optimistic priors - exposure to peer ratings can improve welfare by steering adoption toward the efficient benchmark.
 By contrast,
 when ratings shift beliefs away from true relative performance,
 either by overstating or understating seed performance relative to farmers’ priors,
 the treatment may induce over- or under-adoption and generate welfare losses.
 Importantly,
 the treatment can affect beliefs and adoption regardless;
 however,
 only when peer ratings move beliefs closer to the true performance of seed sold through agro-dealers relative to outside options,
 can the resulting behavioral changes be interpreted as welfare-improving.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Testable implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conceptual framework generates a set of testable implications that guide the empirical analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The treatment shifts average perceived seed performance,
 with stronger effects among farmers who have not previously purchased seed from agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The treatment affects adoption of seed purchased from agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Under the conditional welfare assumption,
 the treatment improves harvest outcomes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Treatment effects occur without improvements in seed performance or agro-dealer switching.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Experimental design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Randomization and power
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsection: Experimental design"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Randomization is conducted at the agro-dealer catchment-area level with equal assignment probability.
 Catchment areas consist of geographically proximate clusters of towns,
 villages,
 markets,
 trading centers,
 and other key hubs,
 and typically include several agro-dealers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To define these areas,
 we used a haversine function to construct an adjacency matrix based on GPS coordinates,
 assigning agro-dealers less than five kilometers apart to the same catchment area.
 The five-kilometer threshold was selected based on a visual inspection of the map,
 the average village size in our sample,
 and the reported distance between farmers and agro-dealers in survey data from a previous study of the maize value chain,
 available 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/PIMMVC/tree/master/data/public"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fn:The-haversine-function"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Randomizing at this level allows us to identify farmer-level treatment effects,
 as all farmers within a catchment area are exposed to the same information environment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sample sizes were determined using simulation-based power calculations based on data from prior surveys,
 allowing power to be assessed under empirically relevant outcome distributions at both the farmer and agro-dealer levels.
 Full details are provided in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "pre-analysis plan"
target "https://www.socialscienceregistry.org/trials/6361"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 (AEA RCT Registry,
 RCT ID 0006361).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Specifically,
 we used data from 78 agro-dealers and 1,529 smallholder farmers in their catchment areas,
 gathered from three districts in eastern Uganda in July 2019.
 These data are publicly accessible 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "here"
target "https://github.com/bjvca/PIMMVC/tree/master/data/public"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The simulations indicate that with more than 112 catchment areas,
 our experiment achieves 80% power to detect effects on a selection of primary outcomes.
 This corresponds to approximately 318 agro-dealers.
 Further simulations at the farm-household level guided our decision to sample ten farmers per agro-dealer,
 resulting in a total sample size of 3,180 households.
 These figures represent the minimum required sample size;
 the actual sample size,
 including the number of agro-dealers and farmers per treatment arm,
 is detailed in the Sample Subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Sample"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Second,
 randomizing at the individual agro-dealer level raises ethical concerns.
 When two or more agro-dealers operate in close proximity,
 treating only one could create unfair competitive advantages or disadvantages.
 Randomizing at the catchment area level mitigates this risk.
 Third,
 it reduces the likelihood of spillovers from treated to control agro-dealers.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

