\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Advantages relative to alternative sources of information about seed performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several alternative sources of information help farmers form expectations about seed performance.
 Seed companies attempt to signal performance through branding and packaging.
 However,
 evidence suggests that farmers do not always respond to these signals:
 without training on seed purchasing,
 they fail to discount compromised bags even when packaging provides cues about performance 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gharib2021fear"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another approach involves regulatory seed quality assurance systems,
 including standards and certification.
 However,
 in settings where institutional capacity to implement and enforce these systems is limited,
 their effectiveness is often constrained.
 In addition,
 when trust in government institutions is low,
 regulatory signals may be perceived as less credible than decentralized information.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marketing,
 standards,
 and certification also reach farmers primarily at the point of sale,
 when they visit agro-dealers.
 This limits their relevance for farmers who rarely engage with the formal seed market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Moreover,
 formal quality assurance systems typically emphasize varietal purity – verifying that seed corresponds to the declared variety and possesses the claimed genetic traits.
 Yet other dimensions of seed quality are also relevant to farmers,
 particularly seed performance,
 reflected in germination and yield.
 In contexts where seed handling and storage may be poor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "BARRIGA2020104928"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 a seed batch may be varietally pure but still perform poorly.
 Although objective methods such as DNA fingerprinting can measure varietal purity precisely,
 peer assessments by farmers operating under similar conditions may better reflect the dimensions of seed quality that matter most to farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The rating system studied in this paper addresses several of these limitations.
 By aggregating the experiences of farmers who planted seed purchased from agro-dealers,
 the system provides a signal based on realized seed performance under local conditions,
 capturing the full range of seed quality dimensions that matter to farmers.
 These ratings are communicated directly through SMS and enumerator visits,
 allowing the information to reach farmers who do not typically purchase seed from agro-dealers.
 Because the signal is generated by farmers rather than regulatory institutions,
 it does not rely on institutional capacity or government trust.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 the intervention is agnostic with respect to seed performance.
 If seed sold by agro-dealers performs poorly – as suggested in some studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bold2017lemon,BARRIGA2020104928,Ilukor2025"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 – aggregated ratings will reflect this rather than systematically steering farmers toward low-performing sellers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Empirical strategy
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "section: Empirical strategy"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate intention-to-treat effects using Ordinary Least Squares:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y_{ij}=\alpha+\beta T_{j}+\gamma'X_{ij}+\delta Y_{0ij}+\varepsilon_{ij}\label{eq:one-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the outcome for farmer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 in catchment area 
\emph on
j
\emph default
,
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{0ij}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding mean-centered baseline outcome,
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a binary indicator for treatment assignment,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{ij}$
\end_inset

 includes controls for orthogonal treatments in the factorial design,
 as the study was embedded in a larger project with additional cross-randomized interventions (demeaned and interacted with the main treatment effect;
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "lin2013agnostic,muralidharan2023factorial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 captures the intention-to-treat effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We estimate analogous specifications for agro-dealer-level outcomes,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{ij}$
\end_inset

 denotes the outcome for agro-dealer 
\emph on
i
\emph default
 in catchment area 
\emph on
j
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since randomization occurs at the catchment area level,
 we cluster standard errors accordingly.
 For farmer-level outcomes,
 we use the conventional sandwich estimator without small-sample corrections.
 For agro-dealer-level outcomes,
 we apply the Bell-McCaffrey adjustment to account for the smaller number of observations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "imbenskole"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We trim continuous outcomes to limit the influence of outliers and apply inverse hyperbolic sine transformations to skewed variables.
 Outcomes with limited variation,
 defined as having 95% or more of observations at a single value within the relevant sample,
 are excluded from the analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To account for multiple hypothesis testing,
 we aggregate related outcomes into summary indices following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 which assigns lower weights to highly correlated outcomes and thereby concentrates information.
 As a robustness check,
 we also compute summary indices following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "kling2007experimental"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While these indices capture overall effects across outcome families,
 we also report treatment effects on individual outcomes to aid interpretation,
 with individual significance treated cautiously.
\end_layout

