\begin_layout Subsection
Rating data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At endline,
 the dyadic rating dataset comprises 16,823 farmer-dealer links.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In 61% of cases,
 farmers reported knowing the dealer they were asked to rate.
 Among those who knew the dealer,
 21% had personally purchased seed there.
 Among those without direct purchase experience,
 2% reported knowing someone who had purchased seed from that dealer.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Among farmers who provided at least one rating,
 the average farmer rated 1.4 agro-dealers (min = 1,
 max = 10).
 The average agro-dealer was rated by 6.7 farmers (min = 0,
 max = 30).
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Restricting to dealers who received at least one rating,
 the average number of farmers per dealer is 7.085 (min = 1,
 max = 30).
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because ratings could be provided either by farmers who had personally purchased seed from the agro-dealer or by those who knew someone who had,
 the signal may reflect indirect information rather than firsthand performance experience.
 In practice,
 93% of ratings were provided by farmers with direct purchase experience,
 and ratings are nearly identical between purchasers and non-purchasers (see Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
 This suggests that the aggregate signal predominantly reflects direct experience.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ratings may also reflect factors unrelated to seed performance,
 such as customer service or personal relationships.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides suggestive evidence that ratings are associated with observable characteristics plausibly related to seller and seed performance:
 specialized agro-shops and dealers with better seed handling practices receive higher ratings,
 and seed ratings on randomly selected fields are positively correlated with maize yields.
 These patterns are consistent with ratings reflecting farmers’ assessments of seed performance rather than purely non-performance attributes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "A.4 Agro-dealer rating patterns"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 provides additional detail on the rating data,
 including the distribution of ratings across the six performance dimensions and their inter-correlations.
\end_layout

