\begin_layout Subsection
Perceived seed performance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects of clearinghouse on farmer perceptions"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 reports treatment effects on farmers’ perceived performance of maize seed sold by agro-dealers.
 Perceived performance is measured using an index that combines ratings across six performance dimensions for agro-dealers in the farmer’s catchment area,
 aggregated at the farmer level.
 Because the index requires farmers to provide non-missing ratings on all six dimensions for at least one agro-dealer,
 the estimation sample is smaller than the full survey sample.
 Treatment effects can be estimated only at endline,
 as only treated farmers provided ratings at baseline and midline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The treatment increases the perception index by 0.09 standard deviations in the full sample,
 with the effect significant at the 10% level (Column (2)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next examine heterogeneity by prior purchasing experience at agro-dealers,
 proxied by whether farmers used high-yielding maize seed purchased from an agro-dealer on any plot in the season preceding baseline.
 The treatment effect is larger among farmers without prior purchasing experience (Column (4)).
 Importantly,
 the farmers who provided ratings – primarily those with firsthand purchasing experience – differ from those who received them,
 which include both purchasers and non-purchasers.
 This asymmetry increases the likelihood that the information encountered diverged from prior beliefs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 these findings are consistent with the rating information being more favorable than farmers’ prior beliefs,
 leading to an upward revision in the perceived performance of maize seed sold by agro-dealers.
\end_layout

