\begin_layout Subsection
Adoption and sourcing decisions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "6.2 Adoption and sourcing decisions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We examine whether the intervention affects seed adoption and sourcing decisions (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on farmer outcomes at end of causal chain: Adoption"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

).
 The treatment increases the 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "anderson2008multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 index at both midline and endline,
 with effects significant at the 5% level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Focusing on sourcing decisions across all plots,
 treated farmers are about six percentage points more likely to report purchasing high-yielding maize seed from an agro-dealer at midline – an increase of 18% relative to the baseline mean.
 At endline,
 the effect declines to roughly three percentage points and is no longer statistically significant.
 We detect no effect on quantities purchased conditional on buying,
 indicating that the intervention operates primarily at the extensive rather than the intensive margin.
 Treated farmers are also more likely to report 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

using any high-yielding maize variety (such as an OPV or hybrid seed) on any of their plots,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with effects of 3.5 percentage points at midline and 4.2 percentage points at endline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evidence from a randomly selected plot confirms these patterns.
 The likelihood that seed was obtained from an agro-dealer increases by nearly five percentage points at midline – an increase of 14% relative to the baseline mean – and by four percentage points at endline.
 Treated farmers are correspondingly less likely to rely on farmer-saved seed,
 with a significant reduction at midline.
 Maize seed expenditure on the random plot also increases significantly.
 Effects on the use of hybrids or OPVs are positive but statistically insignificant.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Farmers reported the maize variety planted in the previous season.
 Varieties were classified as hybrid maize seed/OPV if they corresponded to improved types (e.g.,
 Longe series,
 Bazooka,
 Panner,
 Wema,
 KH series) and the seed was newly purchased rather than recycled or farmer-saved.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taken together,
 the results show that exposure to aggregated peer ratings increases engagement with agro-dealers and shifts farmers away from farmer-saved seed.
\end_layout

