\begin_layout Subsection
Productivity and harvest outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We examine harvest outcomes for farmers (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "Effects on farmer outcomes at end of causal chain: Harvest"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 measured on a randomly selected maize plot and including production,
 plot size,
 yield,
 the value of maize production at market prices net of seed costs,
 the quantity of maize retained for use as seed in the following season,
 and quantity sold,
 sales price,
 and total maize revenue.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The overall index shows a positive treatment effect at endline.
 Treated farmers achieve higher yields,
 increasing by 56 kilograms per acre (13% over the baseline mean,
 significant at the 1% level).
 The value of maize production net of seed costs is 66,000 UGX higher for treated farmers (approximately 18 USD at the time of the survey).
 Treated farmers retain less maize for seed at midline,
 indicating reduced reliance on farmer-saved seed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We detect no effects on quantity sold or total maize revenue,
 consistent with the low baseline level of maize sales and suggesting that additional output is consumed within the household rather than sold.
\end_layout

