\begin_layout Subsection
Alternative mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Search costs and agro-dealer switching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One alternative explanation for the treatment effects is that the intervention reduces farmers’ search costs.
 By increasing market transparency,
 the treatment may enable farmers to identify agro-dealers selling higher-performing products and switch to them,
 potentially leading to the exit of agro-dealers selling lower-performing products and thereby reducing adverse selection in the market.
 Similar dynamics are documented in settings where increased transparency allows buyers to screen sellers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "10.1257/aer.20161965,laneetal,NBERw33082,Hsu2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 as well as in a recent literature showing that reducing non-price search frictions can improve market functioning in low- and middle-income countries 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "NBERw28100,Rudder2024,NBERw33221,Startz2024,10.1093/ej/ueaf009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This relates to a recent literature on non-price search frictions in low- and middle-income countries.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "NBERw28100"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 examine how search and information frictions affect global e-commerce using data from AliExpress,
 showing through a randomized experiment that accumulated sales help overcome these barriers.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Startz2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 estimates that eliminating search frictions faced by Nigerian importers would raise welfare from imported goods by approximately 5%.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "NBERw33221"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 study an SMS-based platform that connects buyers and sellers in Ugandan agricultural markets,
 finding that reduced search costs led to greater market integration,
 increased trade,
 and price convergence.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1093/ej/ueaf009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that Tanzanian small and medium firms randomly listed in a “yellow pages” telephone directory expand their communication networks and increase sales.
 However,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Rudder2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that such exposure does not increase the number of new trading partners but instead enhances firms’ reputations,
 enabling them to secure better terms from existing partners.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
deleted:
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "laneetal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that in Kenya,
 passengers chose safer buses after safety information was publicly disclosed.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "NBERw33082"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that randomized referrals between supplier and client firms in China’s writing brush industry lowered search costs,
 boosting transactions,
 firm performance,
 and product quality as firms reallocated to better partners.
 In our context,
 however,
 even with improved ability to screen for quality,
 farmers did not switch to higher-quality sellers,
 contributing further evidence on the limits of demand-side adjustment in response to enhanced transparency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1257/aer.20161965"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that the spread of mobile phones in India enabled consumers to learn about non-local boat-builders,
 driving market integration,
 improving product quality,
 and lower quality-adjusted prices.
 High-quality firms expanded while low-quality firms exited.
 Closely related to our context,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hsu2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 train farmers in rural Kenya to identify quality-verified hybrid maize seeds.
 While this intervention benefits farmers,
 local sellers do not respond by upgrading quality or adjusting prices.
 Instead,
 many exit the market – likely because better-informed buyers reduce profit margins,
 and upgrading quality may be too costly.
\end_layout

\end_inset


