\begin_layout Plain Layout
Other studies show that the presence of a high-quality seller can strengthen reputational incentives for competitors,
 motivating them to improve quality to remain viable.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "10.1162/rest_a_00758"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that the entry of a chain store offering high-quality,
 low-cost drugs in India prompted incumbent retailers to raise drug quality and reduce prices.
 Similarly,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bjorkman2022can"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 examine Uganda’s antimalarial drug market and show that the random introduction of a retailer selling authentic,
 underpriced medication decreased the prevalence of counterfeit drugs among incumbents,
 while simultaneously improving overall drug quality and lowering prices.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To assess whether the intervention operates through this alternative channel,
 we examine whether treated farmers are more likely to switch agro-dealers between seasons.
 The analysis is restricted to farmers who purchase maize seed from an agro-input shop for at least one plot in both the reference season (baseline or midline) and the subsequent season (midline or endline),
 as switching is only meaningful for farmers who purchase seed in both periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "switchingfarmers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 show that 59% of farmers who purchase maize seed at both baseline and midline switch agro-dealers between those two seasons.
 The treatment does not increase switching.
 If anything,
 treated farmers are slightly less likely to switch at midline,
 with the difference statistically significant at the 10% level.
 By endline,
 switching rates are statistically indistinguishable between treatment and control groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results provide no evidence that the intervention reduces search frictions or induces reallocation across agro-dealers.
 Instead,
 the findings are more consistent with the belief-updating mechanism outlined in the conceptual framework:
 the intervention appears to influence whether farmers engage with agro-dealers rather than which agro-dealer they choose.
 This finding is consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hasanain2019no"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 who implement a similar crowd-sourced information platform in Pakistan’s artificial insemination for livestock market and find no evidence that farmers switch to higher-performance veterinarians.
\end_layout

